<div xmlns:java="http://xml.apache.org/xslt/java" id="centre_col"><!-- begin original content --><h1>ESSUM37400 - Approval of schemes:
Establishing a scheme</h1>
<br>
<p>The scheme must be established by a company before it can be
approved by HM Revenue and Customs; documentary evidence of this
will need to be produced prior to the approval of any scheme. This
means the scheme must have come into existence from a legal point
of view.
<br>
<br> Companies should take their own legal advice on how a scheme
should be set up. Establishment is generally by resolution of the
company's shareholders in general meeting. In some cases directors
may have powers to establish a scheme under the company's Articles
of Association. Scheme advisors should not advise on the powers of
directors, which are a matter of company law.
<br>
<br> The relevant Companies Act requirements on passing
resolutions are at Section 30(1) Companies Act 2006. The procedures
by which private companies must pass resolutions can be found at
sections 288 &amp; 289 Companies Act 2006.</p>
<br>
<h3>The scheme</h3>
<p>Paragraph 45(2) gives the HM Revenue and Customs power to
request "such particulars" and "such evidence" to be submitted in
writing as are required to consider applications for approval. In
practice this means requesting those documents which are considered
to form part of the scheme as a whole.
<br>
<br> In considering what forms part of a scheme, it is necessary
to decide from the evidence in each case what is and is not
relevant. Scheme advisors should consider the following to be part
of the scheme:</p>
<br>
<ul>
<li class="filledcircle">the scheme rules and the ancillary
documents to be used in operating them</li>
<li class="filledcircle">the provisions in the company's Articles
of Association which regulate the shares and therefore affect the
operation of the scheme</li>
<li class="filledcircle">the terms of any shareholders agreements
to which shares acquired under the scheme may be subject</li>
<li class="filledcircle">any arrangements made between the scheme
operators and the scheme participants, including the terms of any
Trust which may hold existing shares used in the scheme.</li>
<li class="filledcircle">invitation documents prepared in
conjunction with the savings carrier or administrator</li>
</ul>
<p>Care should be taken where schemes submitted for approval have
schedules or other schemes annexed to them which do not form part
of the scheme for which approval is being sought. Approval can only
be given to a particular scheme, or an identifiable part of an
overall scheme, which satisfies the relevant requirements of
Schedule 3. If approval is being given only to an identifiable part
of an overall scheme, this should be made clear in the approval
letter.</p>
<br>
<h3>The scheme organiser</h3>
<p>Paragraph 2(2) refers to the "scheme organiser" as the company
which established the scheme. In share option schemes this does not
mean that this company must grant the options.
<br>
<br> If the scheme rules permit options to be granted over</p>
<br>
<ul>
<li class="filledcircle">new issue shares in the company which
established the scheme - the "scheme organiser" company will grant
the options</li>
<li class="filledcircle">new issue shares in the parent company
which controls the "scheme organiser" company - the parent company
may grant the options</li>
<li class="filledcircle">existing shares held by an existing
shareholder (perhaps the trustees of an Employee Benefit Trust) -
it is acceptable for the options to be granted by that existing
shareholder.</li>
</ul>
<p>If the scheme provides scope for options to be granted by
existing shareholders, scheme advisors should ensure that the
arrangements for satisfying the exercise of the options are
satisfactory. For example that the person granting the option has,
at the date of grant, a clear right to have sufficient shares under
his control to transfer to an option-holder whenever an option is
exercised.
<br>
<br> Although options may be granted other than by the company
which established the scheme, they must be granted under the scheme
established by that company (and not by a private arrangement).</p>
<br>
<h3>Group schemes</h3>
<p>Schemes can be extended to include subsidiary companies of which
the company which established the scheme has control. These are
known as &ldquo;group schemes&rdquo;. There is no statutory
authority for extending a scheme to other companies (CIR v Reed
International plc). The scheme organiser company and nominated
subsidiaries are referred to as &ldquo;constituent companies&rdquo;
(paragraph 3(3)).
<br>
<br> A list of the constituent companies should be submitted at
the time the scheme is approved, and subsequent additions or
withdrawals notified to ESSU by the company which established the
scheme. A company&rsquo;s introduction as a constituent company in
a group scheme cannot be backdated to a date before it was formally
admitted.
<br>
<br> A scheme which is established by a company which is itself a
subsidiary company cannot include as constituent companies its own

parent company or fellow subsidiaries.

<br>
<br> &ldquo;Control&rdquo; has the meaning given in section 719

ITEPA 2003 and will normally include companies in which the grantor

owns more than 50% of the shares. Scheme advisors may accept

schemes which also define subsidiary companies by reference to

Section 1159 of the Companies Act 2006.</p>
<br>
